metadata.title: De Havilland Canada Dash 8
aws::graph::propositions: De Havilland Canada Dash 8 Military Variants
CC-142 is a military transport version of the De Havilland Canada Dash 8 for the Canadian Forces in Europe.
CT-142 is a military navigation training version of the De Havilland Canada Dash 8 for the Canadian Forces.
CT-142 is used to train Canadian Air Combat Systems Officers (ACSOs).
CT-142 is used to train Canadian Airborne Electronic Sensor Operators (AESOPs).
CT-142 is used to train allied nations' Air Combat Systems Officers (ACSOs).
CT-142 is used to train allied nations' Airborne Electronic Sensor Operators (AESOPs).
E-9A Widget is a United States Air Force range control aircraft version of the De Havilland Canada Dash 8.
E-9A Widget ensures that overwater military ranges in the Gulf of Mexico are clear of civilian boats during live fire tests.
E-9A Widget ensures that overwater military ranges in the Gulf of Mexico are clear of civilian aircraft during live fire tests.
E-9A Widget ensures that overwater military ranges in the Gulf of Mexico are clear during hazardous military activities.
E-9A Widget is equipped with AN/APS-143(V)-1 radar.
AN/APS-143(V)-1 radar can detect an object in the water as small as a person in a life raft.
AN/APS-143(V)-1 radar can detect small objects from up to 25 miles (40 kilometers) away.
E-9A Widget aircraft operate out of Tyndall Air Force Base in Florida.
Two E-9A Widget aircraft are assigned to the 82nd Aerial Targets Squadron.
The 82nd Aerial Targets Squadron uses E-9A Widget aircraft for the support of training missions.

text:
CC-142
Military transport version for the Canadian Forces in Europe.
CT-142
Military navigation training version for the Canadian Forces. Used to train Canadian and allied nation's ACSOs and AESOPs

E-9A Widget
A United States Air Force range control aircraft that ensures that the overwater military ranges in the Gulf of Mexico are clear of civilian boats and aircraft during live fire tests of air-launched missiles and other hazardous military activities. The E-9A Widget is equipped with AN/APS-143(V)-1 radar that can detect an object in the water as small as a person in a life raft, from up to 25 mi (40 km) away. Aircraft operate out of Tyndall Air Force Base, Florida, with two aircraft assigned to the 82nd Aerial Targets Squadron for the support of training missions.
